Damage development on Antarctic ice shelves sensitive to climate warming

Maaike IzeboudBert WoutersStef Lhermitte

Nature Climate Change

        Article


            17 Oct 2025

Perspective

Published: 31 October 2025

Anticipating climate impacts on nutrition through climate–crop nutrient modelling
                    Bianca Carducci 
            ORCID: orcid.org/0000-0003-3815-30481 na1, Jose Rafael Guarin 
            ORCID: orcid.org/0000-0002-3167-43291,2,3 na1, Kevin Karl1,2, Lewis Ziska4, Meijian Yang1,2, Jessica Fanzo1, Jonas Jägermeyr 
            ORCID: orcid.org/0000-0002-8368-00181,2,5, Alex C. Ruane 
            ORCID: orcid.org/0000-0002-5582-92172, Gerrit Hoogenboom 
            ORCID: orcid.org/0000-0002-1555-05376, Mario Herrero7, Erik Mencos Contreras1,2, Natalie Kozlowski1,2 & …Cynthia Rosenzweig 
            ORCID: orcid.org/0000-0002-8541-22012 Show authors

Nature Climate Change

(2025)Cite this article

Subjects

            AgricultureClimate-change impacts

AbstractMicronutrient deficiencies from poor dietary diversity remain a global health challenge. This issue is exacerbated by climate change-driven extreme weather events that impact crop quantity and quality. While process-based crop models effectively simulate plant nutrient (N, P, K) dynamics for productivity projections, they lack the ability to assess crop nutritional content. This Perspective proposes a framework for integrating nutrient dynamics into crop models for informing nutrition security strategies amid climate change. We delineate key biological pathways influencing nutrient uptake, translocation and density in response to elevated CO2, temperature and low precipitation. We highlight the scarcity of comprehensive datasets, underscoring the need for urgent, collaborative research to amass foundational data and models to ensure nutritional integrity in an uncertain climate.

